&gt; 
&gt; After viewing Mike&#39;s RS 12-469 hack video for the fifth time I felt 
&gt; ready to take the plunge myself, so yesterday while dh was
picking up 
&gt; a pizza at Papa John&#39;s I sneaked next door and bought the radio. He 
&gt; couldn&#39;t stop complaining about how I&#39;d wasted money on a perfectly 
&gt; good piece of equipment only to wreck it for my dumb hobby, but
once 
&gt; we got home he took it upon himself to test it and make sure it 
&gt; worked. For some reason it really DIDN&#39;T work, so he took it
back to 
&gt; RS and exchanged it for another one, and after making sure THAT one 
&gt; worked he even offered to help me with the modification. &quot;No
thanks&quot; 
&gt; I told him. &quot;I think I need to do this myself.&quot; 
&gt; 
&gt; I can&#39;t pretend the process went as smoothly as I&#39;d hoped, but 
&gt; finally I was done and making the last turn in the second screw of 
&gt; the circuit board.. and then.. The whole thing flew out of my hands 
&gt; and both battery wires ripped away from their soldered ends in the 
&gt; casing. It was all Bob could do to keep from gleefully yelling &quot;I 
&gt; knew you were going to break it!&quot; But then I guess he felt bad 
&gt; because he ran down to Walmart and got a soldering iron and solder 
&gt; and spent an hour trying to put it all back together for me. 
&gt; 
&gt; It&#39;s dead as a doornail, and I&#39;m thinking that if I could break it 
&gt; that easily without even knowing how or why, maybe I&#39;m not supposed 
&gt; to pursue this method (sigh). I guess I&#39;ll just think it over and 
&gt; maybe try again later. 
&gt; 
&gt; Thanks for all the helpful information though Mike!
&gt; 
&gt; Robin
